  "footnotes": [
    "Etruscans: the dominant civilization of central Italy before Roman expansion; their origin is debated (indigenous vs Anatolian migration); they taught the Romans the alphabet (via Greek script), religious augury, gladiatorial games, and urban planning; Etruscan civilization was absorbed rather than conquered",
    "Roman Social War (91–87 BCE): Italian allies revolted demanding Roman citizenship; though suppressed militarily, Rome granted citizenship to all of Italy; this transformation from city-state to nation-state was a prerequisite for the Empire",
    "Ostrogothic Kingdom under Theodoric (493–526): the most sophisticated Germanic successor state; Theodoric ruled Italians through Roman law and Romans through Gothic customs; he patronized Boethius and Cassiodorus; his death and Justinian's reconquest war devastated Italy more than the original Germanic invasions",
    "Norman Kingdom of Sicily (1130–1194): Roger II's kingdom was the most cosmopolitan state in 12th-century Europe — Norman, Arab, Byzantine, Jewish, and Latin cultures merged; Arabic was an official court language; Arab geographer Al-Idrisi produced the most accurate world map of the medieval period for Roger's court",
    "Italian city-states and the Renaissance: the fragmented political landscape of northern Italy (Milan, Venice, Genoa, Florence, and dozens of smaller states) created intense commercial and cultural competition that funded the Renaissance; the lack of a centralizing monarchy paradoxically enabled cultural flowering",
    "Risorgimento (1848–1870): the unification of Italy under the Piedmontese Savoy dynasty through the campaigns of Garibaldi, the diplomacy of Cavour, and the wars against Austria; Rome was absorbed in 1870 ending 1,100 years of temporal papal power"
  ]
